ded. Thioguanine therapy should be discontinued if there is evidence of toxic hepatitis or biliary stasis, as reversal of signs and symptoms of liver toxicity have been reported upon withdrawal. Early indications of liver toxicity are signs associated with portal hypertension such as thrombocytopenia out of proportion with neutropenia and splenomegaly. Elevations of liver enzymes have also been reported, but do not always occur.', 'Synergism', 'The risk of hepatic injury should be considered when thioguanine is used with other potentially hepatotoxic agents (e.', 'Moderate', 'pharmacodynamic', NULL, 'https://ddinter2.scbdd.com/server/interact/121186/', '', 'Fluorouracil, Pemetrexed, Cladribine, Trifluridine, Floxuridine, Gemcitabine, Nelarabine, Pralatrexate, Decitabine, Azacitidine, Capecitabine', 'Micafungin, Amphotericin B, Miconazole, Oteseconazole, Flucytosine, Anidulafungin', 1767369485);
